 m. Sarah Odding, d. 1686 Portsmouth RI — 13 children, Town Clerk Portsmouth, large landholder).","mother_research_notes":"Anna Maria Sherman (m. Robert Shearman Jan 8, 1822). Both Robert and Anna descended from Thomas Sherman of Yaxley England (d. 1564) — 5 generations to common Sherman ancestor; Robert spelt name 'Shearman,' Anna spelt 'Sherman.'"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"T01819","date_year":1843,"date_month":11,"date_day":23,"location_city":"Utica","location_state":"New York","children_ids":["T01850","T01851","T01852","T01853","T01854"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott Genealogy","page":"Entry 1819 (as wife)"},{"short":"Findagrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Olivia","middle_name":"Maria","last_name":"Talcott","maiden_name":"Shearman","married_names":["Talcott"],"display_name":"Olivia Maria Shearman Talcott"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"olivia-shearman-1823"},"T01819":{"id":"T01819","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":7,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1812,"month":11,"day":24,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1888,"month":11,"day":10,"city":"Albany","county":"Albany County","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"burial":{"plot_notes":"Albany Rural Cemetery, Albany NY. Findagrave Memorial 11610472. GPS: 42.7058944, -73.7304611.","cemetery_id":"CEM149"},"residence":{"city":"Albany","state":"New York","country":"United States","notes":"Residence at Albany NY for 40+ years."},"parents":{"father_id":"T01802","mother_id":"I00280"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00281","date_year":1843,"date_month":11,"date_day":23,"location_city":"Utica","location_state":"New York","children_ids":["T01850","T01851","T01852","T01853","T01854"],"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1888}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["civil_engineer","engineer","writer","genealogist","veteran","quartermaster_general","yale"],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott Genealogy","page":"Entry 1819"},{"short":"Findagrave Memorial 11610472"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["author","military","engineering"],"notable_blurb":"Compiler of the 1876 Talcott Genealogy book"},"education":[{"institution":"Yale College","location":"New Haven, Connecticut","start_year":1829,"notes":"Entered 1829, left in sophomore year for civil engineering career — one of the few Talcott book entries to attend Yale before leaving."}],"career":[{"role":"Civil Engineer — US-Canada Boundary Survey","organization":"U.S. Government"},{"role":"Civil Engineer — Hudson River Improvement at Albany","organization":"U.S. Government"},{"role":"Civil Engineer — Erie Railroad Surveys (Dunkirk terminus)","organization":"New York and Erie Railroad","notes":"Worked alongside his uncle Andrew Talcott (T01807) who served as Adjunct Chief Engineer of NY&Erie Western Division 1836-37."},{"role":"Civil Engineer — North-East Boundary Survey","organization":"U.S. Government"},{"role":"Civil Engineer — Mississippi River Mouth Improvement","organization":"Coast Survey under Prof. Hassler"},{"role":"Asst. Superintendent of Mineral Lands","organization":"Lake Superior"},{"role":"Mercantile business (briefly)"},{"role":"Brigadier General + Quartermaster General of New York","organization":"New York State Militia (under Gov. Horatio Seymour)","start_year":1862,"notes":"Appointed by Gov. Seymour upon his election in 1862. Served through Seymour's administration with rank of Brigadier General."},{"role":"Genealogist & Author","organization":"Self / Martin & Allardyce (publisher of Goodrich book)","end_year":1888,"notes":"Authored 'Genealogical Notes of New York and New England Families' and 'Talcott Pedigree in England and America from 1558 to 1876' (the latter is the foundational Talcott genealogy used throughout this project as 'the Talcott book'). Also compiled 'The Goodrich family,' rearranged and published by Martin & Allardyce."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"work","header":"Brigadier General who compiled the Talcott Genealogy book","body":"Sebastian Visscher Talcott left Yale in his sophomore year for civil engineering — surveying the US-Canada boundary, the Mississippi delta, and Lake Superior mineral lands. Appointed Quartermaster General of New York with rank of Brigadier General by Governor Horatio Seymour in 1862. He compiled the family's foundational genealogical works including the 1876 'Talcott Pedigree in England and America' that this project uses as its primary Talcott source."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Surveyed US-Canada boundary as civil engineer","body":"Before his Civil War service he worked as a civil engineer across major mid-century projects: the United States–Canada boundary survey, the Hudson River improvement at Albany, the Erie Railroad primary surveys at the Dunkirk terminus, and the Mississippi mouth improvement under Professor Hassler. He also worked as assistant superintendent on the Lake Superior mineral lands."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"New York Quartermaster General appointed by Seymour, 1862","body":"In 1862 Governor Horatio Seymour appointed him Quartermaster General of New York with rank of Brigadier General. He served through Seymour's administration — handling supply, transport, and equipment for New York's massive Union Army contributions to the Civil War."},{"number":4,"category":"death","header":"Wife Olivia died ten months before he did","body":"His wife Olivia Maria Shearman Talcott died at Albany on 29 January 1888 after forty-five years of marriage. He followed her ten months later on 10 November 1888 at age seventy-five; both buried at Albany Rural Cemetery."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"H01628","display_label":"Hooker compiled the parallel 1909 Hooker Genealogy book","link_text":"Cmdr. Edward Hooker (USN)","description":"Sebastian Visscher Talcott (1812-1888) compiled the foundational 'Talcott Pedigree in England and America, 1558-1876' (1876). Cmdr. Edward Hooker U.S.N. (1822-1903) compiled the parallel 'Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker, Hartford Connecticut, 1586-1908' (1909). The two men were distant cousins through the founding generation of Hartford, CT (Rev. Thomas Hooker and John Talcott both arrived 1636). These two volumes are the foundational primary sources for this entire genealogy project."},{"to_person_id":"X02790","type":"parallel_careers","display_label":"Compiled 1876 Talcott parallel to Whittlesey Memorials co-author","notes":"Part of the writing-ancestries CC web — kindred family historians who compiled the foundational printed genealogies underlying this project: Henry Martyn Whittlesey's 1855 first Whittlesey family history (HD3790); Charles Barnes Whittlesey's co-compiled Whittlesey Memorials (X02790); Sebastian Visscher Talcott's Talcott Pedigree 1876 (T01819); Cmdr. Edward Hooker's Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker 1909 (H01628); and Sam Hooker's current digital genealogy project (HD3386).","related_id":"X02790","link_text":"Charles Barnes Whittlesey"},{"to_person_id":"HD3790","type":"parallel_careers","display_label":"Compiled 1876 Talcott parallel to Whittlesey's 1855 history","notes":"Part of the writing-ancestries CC web — kindred family historians who compiled the foundational printed genealogies underlying this project: Henry Martyn Whittlesey's 1855 first Whittlesey family history (HD3790); Charles Barnes Whittlesey's co-compiled Whittlesey Memorials (X02790); Sebastian Visscher Talcott's Talcott Pedigree 1876 (T01819); Cmdr. Edward Hooker's Descendants of Rev. Thomas Hooker 1909 (H01628); and Sam Hooker's current digital genealogy project (HD3386).","related_id":"HD3790","link_text":"Col. Henry Martyn Whittlesey"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD1988","display_label":"Wrote 1874 Dwight and 1871 Strong family genealogies","link_text":"Benjamin Woodbridge Dwight"},{"type":"artifact","related_id":"X03136","display_label":"the congressman he recorded in his genealogical notes"}],"bio":{"title":"Brig. Gen.","first_name":"Sebastian","middle_name":"Visscher","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"display_name":"Brig. Gen. Sebastian Visscher Talcott","photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2005/236/11610472_112501679687.jpg"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST0044"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sebastian-talcott-1812"},"T01850":{"id":"T01850","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1844,"state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1895},"burial":{},"parents":{"father_id":"T01819","mother_id":"I00281"},"marriages":[],"tags":["not_yet_fully_entered"],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott Genealogy","page":"Entry 1850"},{"short":"Findagrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[],"cross_connection